Suppose in R, you have the following factor `x` from which you are tring to subset `y` as shown below. Which of the following option would return TRUE? [see_image_1] #RStats #DataScience [TimeStamp:15092021123051] https://t.co/OEmdv4l65o

Correct Ans: `all.equal(levels(x), levels(y))`. Indexing a vector with character vectors only works when the given vector has same names, otherwise `NA` is returned. @statquant @rstatstweet As I alluded to earlier, one way to help with this is to group computations into batches as only run those batches in parallel to force the cost of the computation to be more than the cost of the parallelism. This works quite well in #rstats if total computation is big enough 6/?

@statquant @rstatstweet (2) is 'always' going to be slow (how slow depends primarily on how many row subsets) because we are talking about data churn every time you subset a df on rows in #rstats 2/?

@statquant @rstatstweet @Bioconductor AFAIK for high level base #rstats {parallel} parallelism, e.g., via mclapply, you have to do that chunking yourself, but if you do the wins could potentially be quite large compared to the net loss you're now seeing.
